26. sceleratorum militum. Erasmus had a great horror of the vagabond mercenary soldiers. They were the curse of the time. See Dialogue X, The soldier and the Carthusian.

28. ut bellum suscipiant cum aquila, i.e. the Imperial Eagle of Oharles V.

30. exemplum scarabaei. He is alluding to the Latin proverb, ⁴ The beetle pursues the eagle,’ which is founded on the fable in which the beetle avenges itself for an insult by destroying the eagle’s egge. Erasmus in his Adayia (where many old proverbe are made texts for little essays on current affairs) bases hereon a satire on the misdeeds of great monarche, who are typified by the eagle.
